<LegalLayout
  title="Help for Uninsured & Self-Pay Patients"
  description="Understand hospital bills and check fair prices when you pay out of pocket."
  crumbs={[{ label: 'For Uninsured' }]}
>
  <p>
    Without insurance, itemized bills can feel overwhelming — and hospitals often charge
    <strong>chargemaster rates</strong> far above what Medicare or insured patients pay. You have
    more leverage than you might think.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 1: Get an itemized bill</h2>
  <p>
    Request a line-by-line statement with CPT or HCPCS codes, dates of service, and amounts. You need
    codes to compare prices fairly.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 2: Check Medicare benchmarks</h2>
  <p>
    Medicare publishes allowed amounts for nearly every procedure. They are a public anchor — not what
    you must pay, but a reference for questions. Use our calculator:
  </p>
  <p>
    <a href="/tools/fair-price/" class="btn btn--primary">Fair Price Calculator</a>
  </p>

  <h2>Step 3: Ask about self-pay discounts</h2>
  <p>
    Many hospitals offer cash, prompt-pay, or financial assistance programs. Ask before paying the full
    balance — especially if your charge is well above the Medicare-based fair range.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 4: Read our CPT guides</h2>
  <p>
    Look up the codes on your bill in our <a href="/codes/">CPT encyclopedia</a> for plain-English
    explanations and typical cost context.
  </p>

  <p>
    <a href="/learn/cpt-codes-explained/">What is a CPT code? →</a> ·
    <a href="/methodology/price-benchmarks/">How we define fair range →</a>
  </p>
</LegalLayout>
